<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-14">
  <title>Resources for 9/14</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify when a function is <em>increasing</em> and when it is <em>decreasing</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize the formula of a <em>linear function</em> (i.e. <m>f(x) = ax + b</m>, where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret a linear function as a function where the average rate of change between every pair of points is the same.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-interpretation-arc">
    <title>Video &amp; Interpretations of Average Rate of Change</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>interpreting average rate of change</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="vZJFNqPUXpM" />

    <example>
      <title>Average Rate of Change (Interpretation, Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        The following problems are to help you understand increasing and decreasing functions better.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>t</m> be the time in days this year, where <m>t=1</m> is January 1 and <m>t=365</m> is December 31.  Let <m>D(t)</m> be the number of hours of daylight on day <m>t</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the domain of the function?  What would you expect the range to be approximately?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Describe when you would expect <m>D(t)</m> to be increasing and when it would be decreasing.  Use dates for <m>t</m> rather than the actual numbers if that makes your life easier.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose a business sells a product.  At price <m>p</m>, they sell <m>d(p)</m> units of the product.  Would you expect the function to be decreasing, increasing, sometimes decreasing and sometimes increasing, or neither increasing nor decreasing?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you have a function <m>f</m> whose domain is <m>[2,9]</m> (i.e. all real numbers <m>x</m> with <m>2 \le x \le 9</m>).  Suppose also that <m>f(2)=3</m> and that the average rate of change of <m>f</m> between <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=9</m> is 2.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Determine the point on the graph where <m>x=9</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Draw a possible graph where <m>f</m> is always increasing on <m>[2,9]</m>, or explain why that is not possible.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Draw a possible graph where <m>f</m> is always decreasing on <m>[2,9]</m>, or explain why that is not possible.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Draw a possible graph where <m>f</m> is sometimes decreasing and sometimes increasing on <m>[2,9]</m>, or explain why that is not possible.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-linear">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Linear Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>linear functions</em>. It is followed by links to two sets of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="NrnYUrKXxF8" />

    <example>
      <title>Introduction to Linear Functions (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        The following problems are to help you understand linear functions better.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>f</m> be a function such that <m>f(4)=7</m>, and the average rate of change between every pair of points is <m>\frac23</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use the given information to find four points on the graph.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Plot the points carefully on paper (or on Desmos).  What does the graph look like?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider the function <m>f</m> given by <m>f(x)=8x+3</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the average rate of change of <m>f</m> between <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=5</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the average rate of change between <m>x=a</m> and <m>x=b</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Graph the function on Desmos.  What shape is it?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Look back at the function in #1 (i.e. <m>f(4)=7</m> and ARC of <m>\frac23</m>).  Recall that if <m>x</m> is the input of the function, then <m>f(x)</m> is the output.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is one way of writing the average rate of change between the inputs <m>x</m> and 4?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is another way of writing the average rate of change between the inputs <m>x</m> and 4?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use your answers to (a) and (b) to make an equation involving <m>x</m> and <m>f(x)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use your equation in (c) to find a formula for <m>f(x)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Computing Linear Functions</title>
      <p>
        In #1 and #2, find a formula for each of the following linear functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The average rate of change (i.e. slope) is 4, and <m>(2,9)</m> is one of the points on the graph of the function.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Two of the points on the graph of the function are <m>(4,3)</m> and <m>(7,-8)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Based on the examples you have seen, what is the average rate of change (i.e. slope) for the function <m>f(x) = 14x-10</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              (Not on quiz) Find the formula for the linear function whose graph includes the point <m>(3,1)</m> and is parallel to the graph of <m>3x+2y=3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

